{
  "texts": [
    "Cryptomite for randomness extraction in (Q)RNGIn random number generation (RNG), randomness extraction is used to process the raw output from an entropy source (sometimes called the noise source) into the final output that is ϵ-perfectly random -a process analogous to conditioning in the NIST standards [68].",
    "In most protocols for quantum RNG (QRNG), this is done using (strong) seeded randomness extractors.",
    "To showcase Cryptomite for RNG, we replicate and extend the randomness extraction step of the semi-device-independent QRNG based on heterodyne detection [65], again giving code examples.In [65], the randomness extractor error is chosen to be ϵ = 10 -10 and the length of the extractor input is n 1 = 6.5 × 10 9 bitsfoot_13.",
    "The experimental results and calculations certify a min-entropy rate of k 1 /n 1 = 0.08943 and, therefore, a total min-entropy of k 1 = ⌊0.08943n 1 ⌋ = 581295000 for the extractor input.",
    "The randomness extraction step is performed using the Toeplitz extractor, which gives an output length of m = 581294933 bits and requires a seed length of n 2 = n 1 + m -1 = 7081294932 bits."
  ]
}